  <\framed>
    <\theorem>
      Every (real, finite dimensional) linear transformation is isomorphic to a real matrix, formally,

      <\equation*>
        \<bbb-R\><rsup|m\<times\>n>\<cong\>\<cal-L\><around*|(|\<bbb-R\><rsup|n>,\<bbb-R\><rsup|m>|)>.
      </equation*>
    </theorem>

    <with|font-series|bold|Informal Proof.> Consider a vector <math|x\<in\>\<bbb-R\><rsup|2>>, rotate <math|x> by <math|\<theta\>> degree. We know that every vector <math|x\<in\>\<bbb-R\><rsup|2>> can be represented by\ 

    <\equation*>
      x<rsub|e>=x<rsub|1>e<rsub|1>+x<rsub|2>e<rsub|2>,
    </equation*>

    where <math|e<rsub|1>=<bmatrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|0>>>>>> and <math|e<rsub|2>=<bmatrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|1>>>>>>.

    <\equation>
      \<cal-A\>x<rsub|e>=x<rsub|1>\<cal-A\>e<rsub|1>+x<rsub|2>\<cal-A\>e<rsub|2><label|eq:lin-trans>
    </equation>

    Note that <smart-ref|eq:lin-trans> can be written as

    <\equation*>
      \<cal-A\>x<rsub|e>=<around*|[|\<cal-A\>e<rsub|1>\|\<cal-A\>e<rsub|2>|]><bmatrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|x<rsub|1>>>|<row|<cell|x<rsub|2>>>>>><above|=|rep>A x<rsub|e>
    </equation*>

    <\equation*>
      A=<matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|cos \<theta\>>|<cell|-sin\<theta\>>>|<row|<cell|sin \<theta\>>|<cell|cos \<theta\>>>>>>.
    </equation*>

    <big-figure|<with|gr-mode|<tuple|group-edit|edit-props>|gr-frame|<tuple|scale|2.52004cm|<tuple|0.5gw|0.5gh>>|gr-geometry|<tuple|geometry|1par|0.6par>|gr-grid|<tuple|empty>|gr-edit-grid-aspect|<tuple|<tuple|axes|none>|<tuple|1|none>|<tuple|10|none>>|gr-edit-grid|<tuple|empty>|gr-arrow-end|\<gtr\>|gr-line-width|2ln|magnify|2.519842099789746|gr-grid-old|<tuple|cartesian|<point|0|0>|1>|gr-edit-grid-old|<tuple|cartesian|<point|0|0>|1>|gr-auto-crop|true|<graphics||<with|line-width|2ln|arrow-end|\<gtr\>|<line|<point|0|0>|<point|1.0|0.0>>>|<with|line-width|2ln|arrow-end|\<gtr\>|<line|<point|0|0>|<point|0.0|1.0>>>|<with|color|blue|line-width|2ln|arrow-end|\<gtr\>|<line|<point|0|0>|<point|0.8000000000000002|0.5>>>|<with|color|blue|line-width|2ln|arrow-end|\<gtr\>|<line|<point|0|0>|<point|-0.6|0.6>>>|<with|color|blue|line-width|2ln|arrow-end|\<gtr\>|<std-arc-counterclockwise|<point|0.3|0.1875>|<point|0.4000000000000001|0.0>|<point|0.4800000000000001|0.3000000000000001>>>|<with|color|blue|<math-at|\<theta\>|<point|0.7|0.146333>>>|<math-at|\<cal-A\>e<rsub|1>|<point|0.951856|0.6>>|<math-at|\<cal-A\>e<rsub|2>|<point|-0.7|0.8>>>>|Geometrical interpretation of linear transformation.>
  </framed>

  <\framed>
    Recall that a vector<nbsp><math|x><nbsp>can be defined without coordinates. The representation

    <equation*|x=<around*|[|<tabular|<tformat|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-halign|c>|<table|<row|<cell|<with|math-level|0|math-display|false|x<rsub|1>>>>|<row|<cell|<with|math-level|0|math-display|false|x<rsub|2>>>>>>>|]>>

    depends on the choice of coordinate system. Denoting by<nbsp><math|x<rsub|e>><nbsp>the representation in the standard basis<nbsp><math|e<rsub|1>,e<rsub|2>>, we write

    <\equation*>
      x=x<rsub|1>e<rsub|1>+x<rsub|2>e<rsub|2><space|1em><above|\<Longleftrightarrow\>|rep><space|1em>x<rsub|e>=<bmatrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|x<rsub|1>>>|<row|<cell|x<rsub|2>>>>>>.
    </equation*>

    For a matrix<nbsp><math|A\<in\>\<bbb-R\><rsup|2\<times\>2>>, written as<nbsp><math|A=<around*|[|<with|mode|text| >\<cal-A\>e<rsub|1>\<mid\>\<cal-A\>e<rsub|2><with|mode|text| >|]>><nbsp>where<nbsp>\<cal-A\><nbsp>is the linear map associated with<nbsp><math|A>, the vector

    <equation*|x<rsub|a>=A<rsup|-1>x<rsub|e>>

    gives the representation of<nbsp><math|x><nbsp>in the coordinate system whose axes are aligned with the column vectors of<nbsp><math|A>.
  </framed>

